	<h1>
From Glee Kid to Computer Whizz
</h1>
	<div class="page-title-hline">&nbsp;</div>
	










<!-- MAIN CONTENT AREA - START -->



		<div class="floatright">
			<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="sidebar" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_sidebar --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_sidebar --> <!-- InstanceEndEditable -->

<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Sidebar" --><!-- InstanceEndEditable --><br class="hide" />
			</div>


			<div class="contentcolumn">
				<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="maincontent" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_maincontent --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_maincontent -->

	<div id="entry-373">
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				
<img alt="DSC_4045.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/DSC_4045.jpg" class="mt-image-left" style="float: left; margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt;" width="220" height="331" />For Ben Mattes, returning to Concordia earlier this spring felt "like coming full circle." He came back to deliver the keynote address for the 2011 Hydro-Québec Montreal Regional Science Fair. His rapt audience was composed primarily of scientifically minded kids from around the city, who had come to Concordia to display their winning science-fair projects in the hopes of progressing to the provincial competition. Mattes could more than identify with them: "When my team won a school-wide science fair in high school, that's when it started to click for me that science was cool."<br /><br />Growing up in the 1980s meant that Mattes was fully immersed in emerging computer culture. As a teenager, he became fascinated with computer games and soon came to realize that he could build them as well as play them. When he graduated from Montreal's renowned Fine Arts Core Education school, FACE, Mattes had to choose between his passion for music ("I really loved choir," he recalls with a laugh) and interest in computers. His project for the grade 11 science fair helped him come down on the side of science. "I did a project on artificial intelligence and taught myself programming ...that, combined with the fact that I was a gamer made it all line up for me. It clicked: this is what I should do for a living."<br /><br />Knowing that he wanted to stay in Montreal, Mattes applied to Bachelors programs at McGill and Concordia. Although he was accepted into both institutions, it was Concordia's Co-op program that sealed the deal. Mattes never looked back, even though he had to drop out of the Co-op program after his first year: he had played too many video games! "My GPA wasn't low enough to be kicked out of the program but I knew I wouldn't have that many choices when it came to internships. So I chose to drop out Co-op and find my own job opportunities." What he found were stimulating jobs in multimedia and CD ROM development that convinced him he was on the right track. Putting his nose to the grindstone, he even managed to graduate early, finishing his Bachelors in Computer Science in three years and one semester.<br /><br />It was 1999 and the dot-com bubble was in full swing. Mattes quickly found a job in web programming with a startup company but after six months, the pressures of full-time work got to be too much. So he took some time off to travel and refocus. When he came back, he was ready to work but the bubble had burst. Luckily, a chance meeting had put him in touch with the CEO of Airborne Entertainment, a small wireless entertainment startup that wanted to get into video games. "It was the perfect fit," Mattes recalls. "They wanted someone young and super ambitious, who would push and push. That was my entry into the industry." After two and a half years with that company and a stint with Game Loft, Mattes landed at Ubisoft, "the behemoth of computer gaming here in Montreal," he smiles. <br /><br />Six years later, Mattes is one of the company's producers, a role that he was happy to embrace: "I realized that I wasn't that great at programming but had solid project management skills. Ultimately at Ubisoft the producer is in charge of the project. They get the funding and they figure out how to get the game made. It's the producer's responsibility to fill in all the holes, to make sure that the game ships on time, on budget, and at a high enough quality." Prince of Persia 2008, the latest game produced under Mattes's helm, definitely met those demands, quickly becoming a popular title amongst gamers. <br /><br />These days, Mattes is producing games on a smaller scale. "The future of gaming lies in mobile and online applications," he explains. Perhaps the future of gaming also lies in the bright young students who came to Concordia earlier this summer to have their own formative experiences at a science fair, and who just might be inspired by Mattes's keynote address to pursue scientific careers of their own.<br />

			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
	
